Introduction¶

Goal of the following report is to demonstrate implementation of a full data analysis workflow based on but not limited to: data acquisition, data wrangling, data integration, data persistence and data analysis using Python and other open source technologies, using the New York City (NYC) Tree Census 2015 and the San Francisco (SF) Tree Census. Objective of our analysis is to gain better understanding of NYC Tree Census, tree population by boroughs of NYC, overall health status, visual representation of the location of surveyed data and comparing common species with Tree Census of SF.

Report consist of the following structure:

  • Data acquisition from two different sources (static and web API)
  • Exploratory data analysis and data wrangle
  • Data sets integration and analysis
  • Queries, cross-tabulation and visualisations
  • Data persistence into 2 different formats (SQLite, HDF5)

For above purposes, we have imported Matplotlib, Pandas, Numpy, Plotly, Gmap, Seaborn and other libraries.

Data Acquisition¶

We acquired data of NYC Tree Census from NYC Open Data web page through API. Dataset included roughly 700 thousand observations and API by default was limited to pull only 50 thousand observations, for our analysis purposes we have manually increased limit to 300 thousand observations.

Based on the instructions to the assignment, second data set was acquired through download of static data set of SF Tree Census and further up load to the python.

According to the NYC Open Data Source, Tree Census information was "conducted by volunteers and staff organized by NYC Parks & Recreation and partner organizations. Tree data collected includes tree species, diameter and perception of health."

  • NYC Open Data Source, retrieved from :https://data.cityofnewyork.us/Environment/2015-Street-Tree-Census-Tree-Data/uvpi-gqnh
  • SF Open Data Source, retrieved from: https://data.sfgov.org/City-Infrastructure/Street-Tree-List/tkzw-k3nq

Inspection and Data Wrangling¶

  • Based on the datafreame inspection, it was found that data Species column includes both Latin and Common names, divided by :: column. Based on non research natures of the this report , it was decided to keep Common names of the tree species.
  • During inspection of the data set, it was noted that some species have many different variations of one species like Skeena Cherries, Bing Cherries, Lapin Cherries and many others. For this specific analysis purposes it was decided to rename those species under one common name (example: all variations of Cherries renamed to Cherry)

As we can observe from the data set, species column (qSpecies) has many unidentified tree names described by "Tree(s) ::" or "::", taking in to the account nature of this exercise, it was decided to drop trees with unidentified names and focus only on common names. Please see below for applymap lambda function for selecting only common names and dropping unidentified trees.

In [119]:
def namechange(x):
    if type(x)==str:
        if '::' in x:
            y = re.sub('.+::','',x)
        else:
            y=x
    else:
        y=x
    return y
test_sf = test_sf.applymap(namechange)

def treename(x):
    if type(x)==str:
        if ' Cherry Plum' in x:
            y = 'purple-leaf plum'
        elif 'Cherry' in x:
            y= 'cherry'
        elif 'Sycamore: London Plane' in x:
            y= 'London planetree'
        elif 'Southern Magnolia' in x:
            y= 'southern magnolia'
        else:
            y=x
    else:
        y=x
    return y
fixed_sf = fixed_sf.applymap(treename)

Comparing amount of similar species in merged data, we were able to see that London Plane tree much more popular in NYC. As per wikipedia due to high population, "The tree is on the NYC Parks Department's list of restricted use species for street tree planting because it constitutes more than 10% of all street trees." Purple leaf plum originally from Southeast Europe, know for its tender weather, is higher populated in SF due to similarities in the weather of its origin. Overall diameter at breast height indicates that London plane tree in average larger in NYC, most probably due to climate, London Plane tree is place of origin native to the Northern Hemisphere

To exercise plotting coordinates of NYC tree census data, two different techniques were selected, based on Google map (gmap) and Seaborn libraries. Based on the documentation and dynamic nature of the Gmap, to visualize the map it must be run at given time, only possible way to save the output in html is to print screen the output and to upload it in to the python (which was done). Also, based on the existing coordinates, seaborn plot was produced (based on the sample of 10 thousand observations), which pretty accurately imitates the map of five boroughs of NYC.

Conclusion¶

Above data sets from various resources provide good opportunity to demonstrate implementation of a full data analysis workflow based on but not limited to: data acquisition, data wrangling, data integration, data persistence and data analysis using Python. Multiple interesting variables allow to draw conclusion based on numerous angles of the data. I truly admire, how much effort was involved in to gathering this data, and considering continuity of the Tree Census data, above analysis may be interesting entry point in to casual analysis of the overall Tree Park of the New York City.
